					   <td>

			
			
			


<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
<tr>
	<td width="1%">&nbsp;</td>
	<td width="98%">

		<table width="100%">
		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    The Magicians Guide</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:milesofsmiles78@hotmail.com">Saerenia Sun</a> | 
		            1/24/2002 4:16:05 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">So you want to be a Magician do you?  <BR>
<BR>
Well, I will not tell you that it is all &quot;Pet kill that&quot; and &quot;Pet kill this&quot;, despite the many differing opinions we Mages do have much more work then just controlling our pets.<BR>
<BR>
What I will tell you however is that being a Mage is one of the most rewarding classes in the game, IF you learn to play well and love your Mage.  Do not create a Mage for the sole purpose of Powerlevelling yourself up to 50 and beyond, but play a Mage because you want to enjoy yourself while at the same time having the choice between grouping and soloing.  <BR>
<BR>
Can a Mage solo you ask?  Why yes, if done properly a Mage can solo quite well.  However, despite contradicting opinions a Mage plays a very important role in a group as well.  But we will discuss this at a later date; for now, let us begin our journey into the life as a Magician.<BR>
<BR>
Ok, so here we are at the character selection screen and you see before you that many, many races and classes.  Well, we know we want to be a Mage, so first I will list which races are able to be Mages, along with a short list of Pros and Cons of each race.<BR>
<BR>
Humans - Average stats, levels slightly faster then the other races, however they have low base intelligence and no night vision.  Do not be deceived however, as there are many, many Intelligence items for sale in Norrath.<BR>
<BR>
High Elf - High charisma, wisdom, decent intelligence, infravision.  The high elves have lower intelligence then the next 3 races,low strength, and are generally better suited to enchanters, but again, at higher levels it is not difficult to change the stats as you see fit.<BR>
<BR>
Gnomes - The short funny little people that everyone seems to love.  Gnomes have the 3rd highest intelligence and high agi and dex, as well as ultravision, and are generally liked in most places.  They are suited to most caster type classes.  Not too mention they are so cute.  Also, at lvl 16 they get a race only skill called tinkering.<BR>
<BR>
Erudite - Ah the superior intellect of the Erudians, they have the highest base intelligence of all the races, yet the lowest base agi and dex and no night vision.  However as a Mage you will receive spells that may compensate this matter.  Many people choose not to be Erudian for the simple fact that their foreheads are so large, others choose them specifically because of their high intelligence. Overall they are a good choice.<BR>
<BR>
Dark Elf - Some would say none compares to the beauty of the Dark Elves, others would say they are evil and must be destroyed.  Be that as it may, they make great Mages as well.  The 2nd highest base intelligence, and high agility, as well as the ability to Hide when danger is near, makes Dark Elves overall great Mages.<BR>
<BR>
	Despite what I have written regarding the various races, each one can be a great and powerful Mage, it is all within the person behind  them.  Will you be a tyrant and worship an evil god, or will you be kind and caring and serve a loving god.  Maybe neutral and joking and serve the gods of neutrality?  Whatever you choose, enjoy it, it will be your home for quite some time.<BR>
<BR>
      Next off to choose where to put those extra ability points.  Well, this is a simple matter really, and it is the same for every race.  Put 25 of those points, yes 25, into Intelligence.  Next put the remaining 5 where you would like them, most would choose Agility, however once your characters agility is at 75 you generally dont need any more points into that stat as the gain is quite low.  I would suggest putting the 5 points into what you think you'll need, maybe dexterity if your dex is low, or strength if your strength is low.  Whichever you choose will be the right choice for you.  As long as you put 25 points into intelligence.<BR>
<BR>
	Next, you must choose a name for your mage, as well as a religion.  Most people choose to be agnostic as in some cases religion may get you into trouble, however, there are beginning to be quite a few religion specific items in the world, and if you have chosen to be agnostic then you will not be able to use them.  It is up to you to decide whom you shall serve.  Each has its own rewards and consequenes.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
      Well my young apprentice, you now are a Mage.  Once you enter your starting location, Ak'Anon for Gnomes, Neriak for Dark Elves, Felwithe for High Elves, Freeport for Humans, and Erudin for Erudites; open your inventory and see what you have in there.  You should have 3 scrolls, 1 is your guild note which you may read by right clicking on it, and 2 are your first spells, also included is a book entitled &quot;Tome of Order and Discord&quot; , you may stick that in your bank or delete it, it is your choice, this book entitles you to become a PvP player.  You should, depending on your race also have a torch or candle, and everyone will start with 5 flasks of water and 5 muffins.  This is your food and water and you will need more later.<BR>
<BR>
	Now right click and hold upon 1 of the 2 spells, it will show its name and mana cost and what level is needed to scribe it.  It should say something like:<BR>
<BR>
Minor Shielding<BR>
Mana: 10<BR>
Spell Level: 1<BR>
Spell Skill: Abjuration<BR>
<BR>
Or<BR>
<BR>
Burst of Flame<BR>
Mana: 7<BR>
Spell Level: 1<BR>
Spell Skill: Evocation<BR>
<BR>
Click on the button on your screen to open your spellbook, it is labeled &quot;Spells&quot; and your spellbook will open.  get used to it, you will spend a lot of time here.  Now click on one of the spell scrolls with the left mouse button and drag it onto one of the empty spots of your spellbook.  Voila! The spell begins to scribe.  Once done, left click on the spell icon in your spellbook and drag it over to the left hand side of the screen into one of the emtpy &quot;Spell Gems&quot; - the little circular slots alongside the screen.<BR>
<BR>
	You will follow this procedure whenever you receive new spells.  As for now, finish with the 2 you have and then head on over to your guild master.  You may ask others for directions or find more information on this website.  While there, hand your guild master the note and he or she will give you a robe and some experience.  Then right click on them and you are able to see the practice skills screen.  Practice 2 points into piercing, and then 1 into evocation, abjuration and channelling.  The others can be practiced at a later level.  Next, equip your robe by left clicking on it and click it over your picture within the inventory screen.  The robe will autoequip, do the same with your dagger. Now head outside of your city and prepare for battle!<BR>
<BR>
  This next section is a levelling guide to get you started with your mage.<BR>
<BR>
Levels 1-5:<BR>
  Hunt in your respective newbie zones, for Dark Elves, along the entrance to Neriak and near the large log(in case you need to run to the guards for help), for Erudites near the guards in case you need them, for High Elves the same, for Humans, most of the area right out in front of the West Gate will be fine for you until Level 5, and for Gnomes there is an area ahead and to the left that will serve as your grounds.<BR>
<BR>
For the inexperienced EQ player:  You should now have 2 spell icons in your spell gem listing, left click on the shield spell and you will cast a spell that will grant you more hitpoints - hp, and armor class - ac.  Next, find a creature wandering about click on it with the left mouse button and hit &quot;C&quot; on the keyboard, this stands for &quot;Consider&quot;, you will want to do this before every single fight.  If the message appears as green then it is not worth your effort, if it is blue then you may win, if it is white, then it will be a tough fight, but you may still win.  If the message is yellow then unless you are in a group it is generally best to not fight the creature(or mob as most call them, which is short for mobile), and if the message is red, then DO NOT fight it, I repeat DO NOT fight it.  There is a HIGH chance that it will kill you.  When in a large group of 4-6 people you will have the chance to kill some mobs that con red to you, but never try it alone. You will die.  When you find a mob that cons blue or white left click on the spell icon that looks like a little flame and you will cast that spell at the mob, then select the autoattack key on the keyboard(defaulted to the ` key, which is located just above Tab) and begin to attack until the mob is dead.  You will gain experience, and some type of faction if it is related to such.(Faction is explained in detail on other portions of this website).<BR>
Now, right click on the corpse of your enemy and you will loot money(if there is any) and see what the mob has on its corpse.  If there is anything, right click on the items and they will pop into your inventory.  Do this for EVERYthing you kill, as you can sell the items to a vendor in your city for money, so that eventually you will have enough to buy your other spells.<BR>
<BR>
When youve gained more money you will want to buy the following spells for Level 1:<BR>
Summon Dagger<BR>
Summon Drink<BR>
Summon Food<BR>
Reclaim Energy<BR>
<BR>
You can buy the remaining others at a later time as they are not important.  The 4 listed above are not important as much either, although if someone is dying of hunger or thirst, and youve got those 2 spells they will be very grateful to you.  And if you die, you can summon yourself another dagger.<BR>
<BR>
Ok, At lvl 4 you will have the option of receiving new spells as well as gaining the skill MEDITATE.  You will learn to LOVE this skill as it increases the rate at which your mana regenerates. (Mana is the blue bar just under your health meter which appears as a red bar under your name - right hand side of screen)<BR>
<BR>
Buy your lvl 4 spells in the following order when money permits:<BR>
Burn - Direct Damage Spell<BR>
Choice of elemental spell - I generally choose Air pet for soloing, and earth of grouping, though others have differing opinions. Choose what you like best for you.<BR>
Fire Flux - Area Effect Spell<BR>
Gate - A VERY handy spell - take you back to your bind point.<BR>
Summon Wisp - If you have no night vision<BR>
Summon Bandages - if your health gets below half you can bind wound up to 50% of your hp.<BR>
<BR>
Then buy the rest when money permits.  Dont waste your money on buying all 4 pet spells as you will be level 8 before you know it and have a new pet.<BR>
<BR>
Now off to hunting from lvls 5-10:<BR>
   Now that you are more experienced I can detail out where to hunt without having to detail exactly HOW to fight.  So lets get started.<BR>
<BR>
High Elves and Gnomes: Ask around for directions to Orc Hill, get in a group or try to solo with your pet and hunt Orc Centurions here until around level 7.  Once 7 go to Crushbone and hunt near the Slaver caves until level 10.<BR>
<BR>
Dark Elves:  Either hunt at the skeleton spawns near the East Commons zone(Ask for help if a Mummy or Zombie spawns) or zone into East Commons and kill black bears, spiderlings and such, and around lvl 7-8 move over into the desert area and kill pumas, rattlesnakes etc.<BR>
<BR>
Humans:  Head to East Commons and kill black bears and spiderlings and then around lvl 7-8 move to the desert area and kill pumas, rattlesnakes, etc.<BR>
<BR>
Erudites:  You should get on the boat and head to Qeynos, then zone into Qeynos Hills and hunt everything that cons blue or white. Or if in a group, head into Blackburrow and hunt there.<BR>
<BR>
For ALL: REMEMBER TO CON EVERYTHING.<BR>
<BR>
At Lvl 8 new spells open up to you, purchase them as money permits in this order.<BR>
<BR>
Flame Bolt - DD Spell<BR>
Shock of Blades - DD Spell that uses Conjuration(Use THIS spell alot, as it will help to max your Conjuration)<BR>
Pick 2 Pet spells to buy - 1 for Solo and 1 for Grouping<BR>
Lesser Shielding - Upgrade to Minor Shielding<BR>
Shield of Fire - a Fire Damage Shield that hurts your enemies when they hit you or whoever you cast this on(it can also be cast on your pet)<BR>
Renew Elements - Pet Healing Spell<BR>
Invisibility - This spell will save your life a lot, use it when trying to get by those nasty mobs that like to ear you for dinner.<BR>
Staff of Tracing - A Summoned Staff that you can give to your pet to use or use your self.<BR>
Eye of Zomm - A summoned Eyeball that you can use to scout out territory (Be careful though if it is attacked they will still come and find you!)<BR>
Dimensional Pocket - Summons 4 slot backpacks that make everything weigh 0, but if you log out before getting the items out they will be taken away as the bags disappear when you leave the game.<BR>
<BR>
Ok, so now youve got all your spells and you are lvl 10 right? Where to go you ask? Well that is simple, here is the listing:<BR>
<BR>
Lvls 10-15:<BR>
High Elves and Gnomes can move on to near the castle and kill Legionairres, Humans can do this as well if they take the boat over to Faydwer.  Erudites can if they make the really long trip, however I would suggest that most races, including Dark Elves head over to one of two places or a mixture of the two.  <BR>
<BR>
1.  West Commonlands is great to hunt in until about 15, start with Plains Cats, and move up to Young Kodiaks, Willowisps, and eventually with a group you can take on the Dervish Cutthroat camp.  There is even an Orc encampment you can take with a group at around lvl 12. Overall a good zone.<BR>
<BR>
2.  Northern Deserts of Ro, kill Orc Raiders, Giant Scarabs and Desert Tarantulas until they are light blue or green, then move over to one of the 3 Dervish camps and get in a group until 15.<BR>
<BR>
Spells to buy at lvl 12 and in what order:<BR>
Pet Spell - Get 2, 1 for solo, 1 for group<BR>
Burnout - Pet Buff Spell<BR>
Bind Affinity - You can change your bind point to anywhere you wish now!<BR>
Rain of Blades - Area Effect Spell that has 3 waves of damage<BR>
Column of Fire - Area Effect Spell that radiates out from the target<BR>
Summon Fang - A piercing weapon you can summon<BR>
Ward Summoned - Good DD Spell against Summoned mobs only<BR>
Cancel Magic - Cancels magic cast on another(Will get rid of GOOD buffs as well - so be careful)<BR>
Summon Elemental Defender - a new Luclin Spell that will create a decent shield for lower lvl Melee type classes.<BR>
<BR>
Lvls 15-20:<BR>
<BR>
Well, by now you are getting the hang of this aren't you?  For these levels you have quite a range of areas in which to hunt.  You can remain in Crushbone but by now it's getting pretty boring, or you can head over to Oasis, which is the prime teen-20's hunting level, hunt Caimans, Crocodiles, Deepwater Caimans, Deepwater Crocodiles, but watch out for Sand Giants, Spectres and Lockjaw. <BR>
<BR>
If sand isn't your thing, then maybe you'd like to fight the undead?  Head on over to Butcherblock, make your way to Dagnor's Cauldron, and then find your way to a little place I love called Estate of Unrest.  This place can take you all the way to 30 and above if you know what you are doing.  Just be VERY careful as the trains here are enormous and VERY Deadly.  And remember, since everything in here is undead, youre invisibility spell will not work against them. It's a great zone though. One of my favorites. <BR>
<BR>
By this time I hope youre getting the hang of the class and know which spells to buy first, the Damage spells, Pet spells, etc...  <BR>
<BR>
I hope this guide has helped you get to Level 20, and if it has, feel free to send me an email, its the first one Ive written.  Above all, ENJOY THE GAME.  Play because you want to play and enjoy yourself, not because you want the best items in the game and you want to be &quot;UBER&quot;.  That is not what playing is about, remember its a game, and it should be FUN.  Dont let others get you down or make you mad, in the end its all about what you decide to do and what you want your character to become.<BR>
<BR>
Enjoy the Magician class, it is one of the best ones in the game! (Note I did not say THE best in the game, as there is NO BEST class, they are all fun and all can be. Just play what you want, but above all HAVE FUN.)<BR>
<BR>
Saerenia Sun<BR>
Dark Elvish Mage of the Tribunal<BR>
<BR>
Email: milesofsmiles78@hotmail.com<BR>
